name: R Ladies Netherlands Book Club - Advanced R Chapter 2
description:
The R Ladies chapters of the Netherlands are partnering up! Starting in April, we'll be hosting an online book club. Our first book is going to be Hadley Wickham's Advanced R. Meetings will take place on zoom every two weeks.

In this first meeting, we'll introduce the idea of having an R-Ladies book club and then Laurel Brehm from R Ladies Nijmegen will present the key points of Chapter 2 (Names and values). After that, we'll go through the exercises together and help each other clear up any doubts and get over any hurdles :) Make sure to read the chapter in advance!

You can find the Advanced R book here: https://adv-r.hadley.nz/
The link to the zoom meeting will be provided closer to the date.
You can find the full schedule and more information here: https://github.com/rladiesnl/book_club

name: R-Ladies Newcastle launch event and social
description:
Please join us for our launch event!

We will introduce R-Ladies Newcastle and its organisers for our first meeting, and ask for feedback from you about events you would like to attend. We will then visualise your responses at the meeting, and socialise afterwards, so we can start building our local community of R-Ladies. Pizza and drinks provided. ‚ÄãWe welcome all levels of R users.

R-Ladies is an inclusive group that welcomes everyone identifying as women or marginalised genders.

UPDATE: Please fill in our survey before the meetup if possible: https://forms.gle/y5UYg67ejczBfCJZA If you can't attend the event, you can still fill in the survey. Thank you!

UPDATE 2: Thanks to our sponsors Sage there will be pizza at the meetup!

We look forward to meeting you!

R-Ladies Newcastle Organising Team

name: June meetup
description:
This will be a tutorial session where you can improve your R skills! Please bring a laptop. We will prepare handouts for the meetup.

For the first part of the session, we will start off with an introduction to R, since we have many beginners in the group. If you are an advanced user, it would be great if you could come along to the first part too, and share your knowledge. For the second part, we will do some more advanced plotting.

There will be some pizza, as well as soft drinks.

Timings:

18:00 Meet and mingle
18:15 Start first part - introduction to R
19:00 Break
19:15 Start second part - advanced plotting
20:00 Optional pub visit

Please have R and RStudio installed on your laptop. The tutorials can be found at github.com/rbolam/RLadiesNCL.

name: July meetup - data visualisation
description:
This will be a tutorial session where you can improve your R skills! Please bring a laptop. If you do not have a laptop, let us know because we have a few for people to borrow. This meetup will be suitable both for beginners and advanced R users.

We will mainly work with the package ggplot2. For beginners, we will introduce the package and its functions, with exercises for you to practice. We will cover how to make different types of plots, how to make subplots, and how to fully customise your plots.

For advanced users, we will look at some more specialised packages, to make ridge plots, use different themes, arrange all your plots nicely, and make chloropleth maps.

Timings:
18:00 Meet and mingle
18:15 Introduction to ggplot2, additional packages, and where to find the resources
18:45 Start tutorials
20:00 Optional pub visit at the Earl of Pitt Street

Please have R and RStudio installed on your laptop.

We will use room 2.022 in the Urban Sciences Building.

If you have any questions, comments or suggestions, you can email us at [masked]

name: August meetup- Summer Social
description:
August meetup ‚Äì Summer Social

We will be building on what we‚Äôve learnt so far and getting to know each other better!

This month‚Äôs meetup will be a chance for our members to build on the skills we worked on in the last meetup using Tidy Tuesday data. More advanced members are also encouraged to attend and show us what they can do with the data.

For the second half of the meetup, we‚Äôll be encouraging you to put your laptops away and get socialising! If so inclined members are welcome to Bring Your Own Bottle, we as organisers will for sure be kicking back with a glass of wine but feel free to bring the beverage of your choice for this part of the meetup. We‚Äôd love to hear about your journey with R (whether a newbie or an experienced user) and share experiences as minority genders in the programming space.

Timings:
18:00 - 20:00 Summer Social
20:00 optional visit to Earl of Pitt Street

We will be in room 2.022 in the Urban Sciences Building.

Please arrive with R and R Studio installed on your laptop. If you would like to be loaned a laptop before the meetup, please get in touch with us in the comments below to request one. We‚Äôd appreciate being given at least a few days notice

name: September meetup
description:
September Meeting ‚Äì Guest tutorial on linear mixed effects models (LMEMs)

This month's meetup will feature a guest tutorial led by Bodo Winter (http://bodowinter.com/) on running Linear Mixed Effects Models in R. He is a lecturer in Linguistics at the University of Birmingham and an accomplished teacher of statistics and R known for his clear and accessible teaching style.

In the first hour of the meetup, Bodo will lead his tutorial, which will be geared toward somewhat more advanced users of R who are interested in applying LMEMs to their data. However, we invite users at all levels to come follow along and ask questions. Don't be worried about it being too advanced -- this tutorial will be useful for people at all levels!

In the second half, we will have pizza and we encourage you to Bring Your Own Bottle (of any sort of beverage you fancy) to enjoy or to share. This will be a time to talk through practical applications of LMEMs for your own work and ask questions of Bodo and the more advanced users. This will be a great opportunity for people comfortable with statistics to ask more advanced methodological questions *as well as* for people who are more new to LMEMs and R to consolidate the tutorial material.

Timings:
18:00 - 19:00 LMEM Tutorial
19:00 - 20:00 Question and Answers and Pizza

We will be in the Urban Sciences Building again (2.022) and the room will be accessible through the main entrance to the building.

Please arrive with R and R Studio installed on your laptop. If you would like to be loaned a laptop before the meetup, please get in touch with us in the comments below to request one. We‚Äôd appreciate being given at least a few days notice.

name: October meetup
description:
We will be having a series of lightning talks from our R-Ladies community! We‚Äôd love to hear from as many of you as possible on how you‚Äôve used R, no matter your level of experience.

It should be an excellent chance to hear about the breadth of R use which is happening in Newcastle.

There will be talks on:
- Using R for eye tracking while reading
- What is Bioinformatics?
- Using factors in R
- Working with satellite data to map forests & forest quality
- Topic modelling
- Disentangling the drivers of predators on coral reefs
- Modelling hierarchical data for children in schools for a language intervention study
and more!

As always, there will be pizza too! We will meet in room 4.005.

If you have any questions, comments or suggestions, you can email us at [masked]

name: November meetup: THE PURDUR EDIT
description:
ENTRANCE IS VIA THE BACK DOOR
Due to Purdur (restrictions placed on government employees in the run up to an election) our scheduled speakers are unable to give public talks.

To stick with our theme of government data science we will instead be running a hands on workshop to investigate election data. We will work in teams to ensure that the workshop is suitable for all levels of R users so come along with a positive attitude and lets get stuck in to some data wrangling and data viz.

Please bring laptops with you for this event. If you need access to a laptop please inform the organisers by Friday 08th of Nov.
We will meet in room 2.022 in the Urban Sciences Building. There will be pizza and soft drinks!

ENTRANCE IS VIA THE BACK DOOR

name: R-Ladies Christmas social and yearly roundup!
description:
We‚Äôll be having our final Meetup of the year to look back on all the great stuff that‚Äôs happened since we began back in May.

Christmasy snacks and pizza will be on offer and your encouraged to bring your own bottle. We‚Äôd love to hear your feedback from this year so far, what you‚Äôd like to see next and what your R goals are for next year!

If you‚Äôve not made it to a meetup this year, then this will be a great opportunity to get to know the community we‚Äôve built so far.

Room 2.022- Entrance will be via the rear door

name: March meetup - data wrangling using the tidyverse
description:
This will be a tutorial session where you can improve your R skills! Please bring a laptop. This meetup will be suitable both for beginners and intermediate R users.

We will work with tidyverse packages and learn how to do data wrangling in R, for example how to change the format of your data, how to combine different dataframes, summarising your data, and dealing with factor levels.

We will meet at 6pm, and then everyone can work on the tutorials. Help will be available.

Please have R and RStudio installed on your laptop, and install the tidyverse (install.packages("tidyverse") ). There will be only limited sockets at the venue, so please charge your laptop before the event.

Location: The Greenhouse, ground floor of Northumbria University Students‚Äô Union.

If you have any questions, comments or suggestions, you can email us at [masked]

name: Panel session and meetup pre-SatRday
description:
R-Ladies Newcastle are pleased to announce we will be hosting a panel¬†session with¬†Julia Silge (https://juliasilge.com/about/), a data scientist and software engineer at R Studio, and¬† Mine √áetinkaya-Rundel (http://www2.stat.duke.edu/~mc301/) a Senior Lecturer in the School of Mathematics at University of Edinburgh and Data Scientist and Professional Educator at RStudio.
¬†
The event will be an opportunity for R-Ladies to meet up prior to the SatRdays event taking place the next day, so if you‚Äôre in Newcastle the night before please come along. If you‚Äôre worried about attending SatRdays alone, then this will be a great chance to meet a few friendly faces who you‚Äôll recognise the next day. Alternatively, if you‚Äôd been on the fence of making the journey to Newcastle hopefully this will act as an extra enticement!
¬†
We're so excited for SatRdays and hope to see as many R-Ladies members as possible. Tickets can be purchased from: https://newcastle2020.satrdays.org/

About the session:
6:00-7:00pm Panel session (approx.)
7:00-8pm Networking
¬†
We need your questions!
¬†
The panel session will be a chance to ask Julia and Mine about their career history as R-Ladies and the different focuses their careers have had. Both have had rich and varied careers, so this is a great chance to hear about their experiences. We‚Äôll be taking some questions on the day, but for the best chance of having your questions answered please submit them in the comments below or message one of us organisers.
¬†
Example questions:
What was it like moving away from academia? And what advice would you give to others thinking about making the transition
What do you think is the most valuable skill you use in your roles as data scientists?
What is your favourite trick in R? E.g. nifty shortcuts, handy functions
What do you look for when joining a new team?
Do you have any advice on making sure we‚Äôre bringing R-Ladies principles in to our jobs?
¬†
We anticipate this event will be well attended so book your place asap. As usual, this event is open to those who identify as a marginalised gender.

Acknowledgements

Thank you to the School of Computing for providing the venue and to Sage for providing pizza.

description:
Hi everyone! The first workshop of 2019 is finally here! This is an introductory workshop to R and RStudio, suitable for those who do not have any experience with R. You will learn how to find your way around RStudio, interact with R, manage your environment and install packages.

You are required to bring your own laptop. Please ensure you have the latest version of R and RStudio installed on your machine. You can download and install the latest version of R from (https://www.r-project.org/) and RStudio from (https://www.rstudio.com/). If you have questions please contact us before the event.

https://www.eventbrite.com/e/r-and-rstudio-intro-for-the-rladies-community-in-brisbane-tickets-58628573642

Look forward to our first workshop of the year!

description:
‚Ä¢ What we'll do
In this first ever meetup of RLadies-Oslo, current head of RLadies-Oslo will present how she adds neuroimaging images to her plots when visualising data. The approaches used should be easily applicable to other types of plots and images that one may want to combine during data visualisation. Questions are very welcome.

There will be some simple food and drink served, and time to mingle.

No equipment necessary. If you want to give the process a try with your own stuff and get aid from the speaker, bring a laptop/MacBook with R and RStudio installed.

name: Hands-on intro to SQL and R with Steph Locke
description:
We are very eager to host Steph Locke from https://itsalocke.com/.

Learn SQL from the comfort of RStudio in this 2.5 hour hands-on workshop. Using SQLite as our database of choice, we'll learn the fundamentals of good data structures, querying single datasets, and combining multiple datasets for getting answers from across your database. Bring your laptop with RStudio and we'll send more info closer to the date on packages to install.

All attendees and speakers must agree to abide by the R-Ladies Code of Conduct: https://github.com/rladies/starter-kit/wiki

Required software and data:

- Software: R & RStudio

- Packages: RSQLite, rmarkdown

- Data: https://www.kaggle.com/gabrio/board-games-dataset

Please make sure you have the software and packages installed prior to coming, and have downloaded the data to a folder you know how to navigate to.

name: Topic modelling - what is it, and how does VG use it?
description:
Topic models (TM) are powerful tools to programmatically uncover textual structure in what otherwise appear to be just plain unstructured text. The applications of TM are many, like content analysis, article search, and personalisation of content. Isabelle Valette will take us through what topic models are, the way the algorithm works, and how VG has been using it inside and outside the newsroom.

Who is Isabelle?
French data nerd, nature lover and week-end hiker, Isabelle works as a data scientist at the media house VG, one of Norway's largest newspaper. Educated as an economist and transformed into an RLady, a computer scientist and data journalist, Isa loves #rstats. She is passionate about empowering women to become awesome coders.

As we are closing in on Christmas, we will also serve som gingerbread (pepperkaker) and gl√∏gg. Bring your self (and a friend?) and a positive attitude!

name: Building shiny dashboards - with Aurora and Lene
description:
In this workshop, Aurora and Lene will take us through the steps of building a shiny dashboard. We will incrementally build the dashboard, with explanations throughout to help you understand how the components act together.

At the end of the workshop, you should have enough basic understanding of shiny to be able to start building your own shiny dashboard.

Prerequisites:

Laptop with a working installation of Rstudio with the following additional packages installed:
shiny,
shinydashboard,
gapminder,
tidyverse,
DT,
plotly

About the Shiny R-ladies:

Aurora is a diverse data scientist in NextBridge Anlytics. She works with innovative and demanding analytical tasks, and has also worked with system developement. Her background is from physics and she has a PhD in the field of quantum mechanics and condensed matter physics. She has long experience from teaching in academia and began using R some years ago due to a demand for a shiny dashboard.

Lene is a physicist turned data scientist. After analysing data for LHC injections at CERN she joined Nextbridge Analytics in 2016. She enjoys working on a wide range of projects using data and algorithms. After being introduced to R for the second time and tidyverse for the first time she really got into R and after learning about R-ladies she was a part of starting up R-ladies Oslo.

Food and refreshments will be provided, a courtesy of NextBridge Analytics.

We look forward to seeing you all!

name: Bayesian methods for rank and preference data with Valeria Vitelli
description:
Bayesian methods for rank and preference data - from recommendation systems to cancer genomics

Ranking items is crucial for collecting information about preferences in many areas, from marketing to politics. The interest often lies both in producing estimates of the consensus ranking of the items, which is shared among users, and in learning individualized preferences of the users, useful for providing personalized recommendations. In the latter task it is particularly relevant to have posterior distributions of individual rankings, since these can provide an evaluation of the uncertainty associated to the estimates, and thus they can avoid unnecessarily spamming the users.

I will present a statistical model which works well in these situations, and which is able of flexibly handling quite different kind of data. The Bayesian paradigm allows a fully probabilistic analysis, and it easily handles missing data and cluster estimation via augmentation procedures.
Interestingly, this Bayesian framework has also proved to be useful for genomic data integration, since typically heterogeneous microarray data are available from different sources, and their combination allows both to gain statistical power and to strengthen the biological insight.

Valeria Vitelli holds a PhD in statistics from Politecnico di Milano, Italy. She was a postdoc at Ecole Centrale Paris for a year, within a research group funded by El√©ctricit√© de France working on big data problems in the energy sector. She then moved to the University of Oslo, where after a 5 years postdoc period funded from the Norwegian Cancer Society she became associate professor in September 2018. Her experience spans over several areas of mathematics and statistics, including functional data analysis with applications in physiology, machine learning (describing people mobility in dense urbanized areas from mobile phone data), and finally statistical genomics of cancer.

name: TidyTuesday - with RLadies Oslo
description:
Every Monday the R for Data Science (R4DS) releases a new dataset on their GitHub that has been tamed, but does not always adhere to ‚Äútidy‚Äù data principles. This dataset will come from an article with an interesting plot. Our goal is to take a look at the raw data, and generate either a copy of the original plot or a novel take on the data! You can obviously use whatever techniques you feel are appropriate, but the data will be organized in a way that tidyverse tools will work well!

We will come together and work in teams helping each other solve this weeks TidyTuesday challenge. TidyTuesdays are a great way to improve R skills and get involved in the community!

* To participate in TidyTuesday, you need to do a few things *

Create and save an image of a plot from R
- Save the code used to recreate your plot (include data tidy steps!)
- Submit the plot and code on Twitter
- Use the #TidyTuesday hashtag (you can also tag me @thomas_mock)
- Browse other submissions and like/comment on their work!

However, that might seem like a lot! So at minimum please submit your plot with the hashtag #TidyTuesday.

* Rules for TidyTuesday *

We welcome all newcomers, enthusiasts, and experts to participate, but be mindful of a few things:

- This is NOT about criticizing the original authors. They are people like you and me and they have feelings. Focus on the data, the charts and improving your own techniques.
- This is NOT about criticizing or tearing down your fellow #RStats practitioners! Be supportive and kind to each other! Like other‚Äôs posts and help promote the #RStats community!
- The data set comes from the source article or the source that the article credits. Be mindful that the data is what it is and Tidy Tuesday is designed to help you practice data visualization and basic data wrangling.
- Use the hashtag #TidyTuesday on Twitter if you create your own version and would like to share it.
- Include a picture of the visualisation when you post to Twitter.
- Include a copy of the code used to create your visualization when you post to Twitter. Comment your code wherever possible to help yourself and others understand your process!
- Focus on improving your craft, even if you end up with someting simple! - Make something quick, but purposeful!
- Give credit to the original data source whenever possible.

- finally, publication quality figures w/ R!

name: RStats Workshop Series: Part I (Jan28‚Äî>Feb04!)
description:
WHO is this for?
- If you are new to R & are short-budgeted on time!
- If you'd like to start working with data in R w/o learning all the programming details first!!
- If you have a neat data set you'd like to explore w/ basic statistics!
- If you are getting started with base R and want to learn more #rstats!

* If any of this is true, this workshop might be for you!
* Come EARLY (545p) for set-up, questions reg. tidyverse

WHAT are we planning?
*RStats Workshop: Part I*
- getting started with R
- exploratory statistics: measures of central tendency & variability, correlations, multi-variate stats
- visualizing statistical analyses: histograms, boxplots/violin plots, scatterplots, bar graphs, saving plots
- Excel/SAS/SPSS vs R?

- Parts II, III of 'Learning Statistics with R' by Dani Navarro (https://learningstatisticswithr.com/book).
- Statistical exploration of the gapminder dataset w/ R

*RStats Workshop: Coming up next*
- Probability Distributions & skew, kurtosis
- Inferential Statistics: hypothesis testing, p-value, confidence intervals
- Handling Missing data: imputation
- Parametric (e.g., ANOVA) & Non-parametric statistical tests
- Principal Component Analysis (PCA) using ggbiplot

name: RStats Workshop Series: Part II
description:
WHO is this for?
- If you are new to R & are short-budgeted on time!
- If you'd like to start working with data in R w/o learning all the programming details first!!
- If you have a neat data set you'd like to explore w/ basic statistics!
- If you are getting started with base R and want to learn more #rstats!

* If any of this is true, this workshop might be for you!
* Come EARLY (545p) for help with set-up, questions reg. tidyverse.

WHAT are we planning?
*RStats Workshop: Part II*
- Using Existing Data OR Loading Yours
- Viewing the Structure of your Data
- Transforming your Data: Basic transformations: z-score, log
- Intro to Probability Distributions: Skewness, Kurtosis
- Checking Normality of Distributions: Shapiro-Wilk vs Kolmogorov-Smirnov, Descriptive stats
- (Intro to) Association Tests: Correlations
- Excel/SAS/SPSS vs R?

* If time permits (if not, part III):
- Hypothesis testing using chi-square tests, t-tests, ANOVAs
- Power analyses
- Handling missing & duplicate data (see R packages ‚ÄòmixRasch‚Äô, ‚Äòmice‚Äô, others)

- Parts III, IV of 'Learning Statistics with R' by Dani Navarro (https://learningstatisticswithr.com/book).
- Statistical exploration of the gapminder dataset w/ R

name: R-Ladies-Boulder Kickoff Meeting!
description:
Hi Boulder useRs! We're excited to get the paRty started with our official kickoff meeting!

We plan to introduce the organizers of the group and, more importantly, get to know all of you, how you use R, and what'd you love to see from this group.

Each organizer (Courtney, Lisa, Marta, and Leigh) will also briefly present a fun and/or useful R package created by a women, so we can all learn something while getting to know each other. So bring your thoughts, ideas, and enthusiasm! You can bet we will.

5:45-6:00pm - Arrival and mingling
6:00-7:00pm - Introductions and presentations
7:00-7:30pm - Wrap up and more mingling

Venue and refreshments graciously provided by SomaLogic.

Can't wait to see you all soon!

name: R Ladies Boulder Meetup #2: TidyTuesday
description:
Hi Boulder UseRs! Join us for this month's R Ladies Meetup: TidyTuesday!

We plan to participate in TidyTuesday, which is a fun, low-stress coding challenge posted weekly by the R4DS online learning community.

** Please bring your laptops!**

The goal of TidyTuesday is to flex your tidyverse muscles for data wrangling and plotting. However, if you're new to tidyverse (or a die-hard base R useR), you are also more than welcome to join! This is a chance to learn from more experienced tidyverse useRs and make new connections at the same time.

For more information on TidyTuesday, see here: https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday

5:45-6:00pm - Arrival and mingling
6:00-6:15pm - Introductions & instructions
6:15-7:15pm - TidyTuesday group coding challenge!

Venue and refreshments graciously provided by SomaLogic.

Can't wait to see you all there!

name: R Ladies Boulder Meetup #4: Ugly Holiday Plot Contest!
description:
Hi Boulder UseRs! Join us for this holiday edition of R Ladies: Ugly Holiday Plot Contest!

This extRa special Meetup is a chance for you to let your holiday enthusiasm loose and share with us your ugliest holiday-themed plots. We will also be at a special location: North Boulder Upslope Brewing Company!

*****Please submit your ugly holiday plots to [masked] by December 9th to be included in the ugly plot contest!***** Those without ugly plot submissions are also welcome to attend! All are encouraged to wear ugly holiday attire. For inspiration: reddit.com/r/DataIsUgly/.

During the meeting we will be showing off all of the lovely ugly plot submissions with the option for submitters to say a few words about their plots if they want! Winners will be selected by categories (think: "most likely to make somebody lose their eyesight" or "most variables plotted at once").

Refreshments graciously provided by SomaLogic.

Can't wait to see you all there!

name: R Ladies Boulder Meetup #5: Introduction to Building R Packages
description:
Hi Boulder UseRs! Join us for this month's R Ladies Meetup: How to build a package!

** Please bring your laptops!**

This month our very own Leigh Alexander will be giving us a tutorial on how to build an R package from the ground up. Package ideas are not required, but are definitely encouraged. All skill levels are of course welcome.

5:45-6:00pm - Arrival and mingling
6:00-7:00pm - Package building with Leigh
7:00-7:15pm - Wrap up

Venue and refreshments graciously provided by SomaLogic. Beverages by donation.

Can't wait to see you all there!

name: R Ladies Boulder Meetup #6: Bring Your Own Code Coding Hour
description:
Hi Boulder UseRs! Join us for this month's R Ladies Meetup: Bring Your Own Code Open Coding Hour!

This month we are hosting an open coding night at The Rayback Collective. This is a casual meetup for people to bring their projects, practice skills, and just mingle and share tips, tricks, and expeRtise. Use this time to work through R tutorials, a TidyTuesday challenge, or your own project.

We'll be there by 5:45pm and people are welcome to hang out until Rayback closes.

Can't wait to see you all there!

name: R Ladies Boulder Meetup #7: Introduction to R Shiny
description:
**NOTE: The parking lot rules have changed at SomaLogic. Please park on the street or in the lot behind the building R Ladies is hosted in (2990 Wilderness Place) to avoid being booted or towed.**

Hi Boulder UseRs! Join us for this month's R Ladies Meetup: Introduction to R Shiny!

** Please bring your laptops & cash for beer donations!**

This month our very own Lisa Moller will be giving us a tutorial on how to build an R Shiny app from scratch. Lisa has been learning Shiny over the last few months and she's excited to share what she's learned with us!

If you've never used Shiny before or have only dabbled, this tutorial is for you! Experienced Shiny users are also encouraged to attend and share your knowledge with the group as we work through the tutorial.

5:45-6:00pm - Arrival and mingling
6:00-7:00pm - Intro to Shiny with Lisa
7:00-7:15pm - Wrap up

Venue and refreshments graciously provided by SomaLogic, **Beverages by donation.**

Can't wait to see you all there!

name: First Meet and Greet
description:
Happy Women's Day to all R-Ladies!
Let's meet, get to know each other, what we expect from the group, and collect ideas (what, where and how) for possible future meetups! :) :)

name: How to Teach R - Brainstorming
description:
Who is invited?
If you've ever tried learning or teaching R, or were curious but could never start off, we invite you to come share your thoughts with us. If you have resources you use to learn or teach R, you can bring these with you!

What we plan to do?
We hope to gather ideas and resources about (1) what one needs to use R effectively - at different stages of learning, (2) what the members of this group would like to learn, (3) what the members of this groups would like to teach, (4) what ways of learning/teaching R work and what don't.

What we plan to achieve?
By the end of these two hours, we hope to have a collection of resources and concrete monthly workshops that R-Ladies can offer over the next few sessions.

name: Starting off in R and R-Studio
description:
In Diesem Workshop w√ºrden wir die Basics von R unterrichten - wie f√§ngt man mit unterschiedlichen Datensets an, was muss man √ºber diese Daten wissen, und wie findet man das heraus. Wir w√ºrden basic programming und visualizations in R kennen lernen. Die Teilnehmer haben auch die Gelegenheit, potentielle Probleme zu diskutieren und Tips auszutauschen. Ziel ist die gemeinsame Erarbeitung von relevanten Werkzeugen f√ºr Einsteiger.

In this workshop we would teach the basics to R - how to start working with different datasets, what one should know about them, and how to evaluate these. We would familiarize ourselves with basic programming and visualizations. Participants would also have the opportunity to discuss potential problems and share tips with each other. The goal is to familiarise beginners to relevant tools

name: Data Transformation and Introduction to Tidyverse
description: We introduce some common data transformation tools and packages for exploring and pre-processing data. We will work through an example data set together, raising and answering a number of questions. Please carry laptops with R and R Studio already installed and running.

name: Data Transformation and Introduction to Tidyverse
description: We introduce some common data transformation tools and packages for exploring and pre-processing data. We will work through an example data set together, raising and answering a number of questions. Please carry laptops with R and R Studio already installed and running.

name: Data Wrangling, Transformation and Communication
description: This month we create an R markdown file!! We take a messy dataset, transform it to a tidy one, all while revising a number of commands from BaseR and Tidyverse. Once we have learnt to wrangle and transform this dataset, we will go a step further, making a simple interactive plot in plotly and using KnitR to create an html document of all that we have learnt.

name: Visualizing Geographical Data
description: This workshop focuses on techniques to visualize different kinds of geographical data and how to plot these on corresponding maps. Material will be provided with the help of a markdown file.

name: Thinking about and exploring data in R
description: We'll work together to think about and solve different data problems using a variety of tools for data wrangling, transformation and plotting.

name: Modeling in R - Part One
description: Regressions, general linear models, mixed models, with a touch of plotting and mapping. We'll cover it all!

name: Modeling in R - Part Two
description: This time we get into the world of GLMs and GLMMs! Please carry laptops with R and R-studio installed.

name: Modeling in R - Part Three
description: This workshop will give us an introduction to machine learning! Please carry laptops with R and R-studio installed.

name: Analysing Twitter Data
description: In this meetup we will learn the basics of accessing, cleaning, wrangling and visualizing Twitter data. If you'd like, you can install the following packages beforehand - "tidyverse", "tm", "rtweet", "wordcloud2" and "tidytext".

name: Tidy Tuesday - Come and practice your R skills
description:
Do you want to practice your R-skills? Do you want to improve your abilities to clean, analyse and plot data?

Then this event is what you need! We will use the data from Tidy Tuesday as an excuse to work with R. We will meet to work independently using the same data-set. Each one can choose which analysis to perform or which tools to use (you can already think what you want to practice or learn). We will do this together to have the opportunity to ask others and because coding together is fun!

This activity is for everyone, from beginners to experts. You will set your own goal. We will have a coffee (or what ever you prefer) while working together. This way we can have the opportunity to ask others, to share ideas and code!!

Tidy Tuesday a weekly data project aimed at the R ecosystem. Every week a new data set is uploaded and analysed by the community, then the plots can be shared! Las week data from the fires in Australia was analysed. Have a look at some of the community plots on Tweeter:

https://twitter.com/hashtag/tidytuesday

Bring your own laptop.

name: Tidy Tuesday - Come and practice your R skills
description:
LAST TIDY TUESDAY!!!

After one and half month of uninterrupted weekly meetups to analyze data we are approaching the end of the Tidy Tuesday Meetings, just before the first anniversary of R-Ladies!!!
If you have not participated yet, do not miss this event! It is a great opportunity to meet us in an informal environment and practice your R-Skills independently of your expertise (from totally beginners to experts). And if you have been regularly coming, do not miss this last Tidy Tuesday Evening!

Hope to see you there!

We will use the data from Tidy Tuesday as an excuse to work with R. We will meet to work independently using the same data-set. Each one can choose which analysis to perform or which tools to use (you can already think what you want to practice or learn). We will do this together to have the opportunity to ask others and because coding together is fun!

So far the R-Ladies Freiburg have been working really hard in producing super nice plots! The idea of this meeting is to share our knowledge. You can have a look at them on:

https://twitter.com/RLadiesFreiburg

This activity is for everyone, from beginners to experts. You will set your own goal. We will have a coffee (or what ever you prefer) while working together. This way we can have the opportunity to ask others, to share ideas and code!!

It is also a great opportunity to start doing analysis to add to your portfolio on line, so that others know what you can do! Have a look at:

https://github.com/kyla-mcconnell/tidy-tuesday

https://github.com/ichisa/TidyTuesday

IMPORTANT:

Bring your own laptop. Hopefully with enough battery.

name: R-Ladies Santa Barbara Chapter Kick-Off Meeting
venue_name: National Center for Ecological Analysis and Synthesis (NCEAS)
description:
Join us for the first ever meeting of the Santa Barbara chapter of R-Ladies!

R-Ladies (https://rladies.org/) is a world-wide organization to promote gender diversity in the R community. At the kick-off meeting we'll introduce the group and organizers, welcome new members, and discuss future events & activities. You'll also get to check out the cool space and new artwork at the National Center for Ecological Analysis and Synthesis (https://www.nceas.ucsb.edu/).

We're looking forward to meeting many R-Ladies and allies in April!

Follow us on twitter: @RLadiesSB

CODE OF CONDUCT

This group was created so those who identify as women (including trans women, genderqueer women, and non-binary people who identify as women or female in a way that is meaningful to them) have a comfortable place to learn. Anyone who violates or has previously violated this community's Code of Conduct will be refused entry, expelled, and/or any other action deemed appropriate by the Organizer, regardless of event registration, meetup membership or other condition.

We are looking for volunteers to give talks! Talks should be between 5-8 minutes. If we get more than 6 talks, we will select a diverse group for this meetup and will make sure to host a similar type of event in the future.

description:

We will have a brief introduction the data and setup, with the maximum time devoted to coding together. The focus will be on making visualizations with `ggplot2`.

name: Level up your R skills & build confidence through small examples w/ Jenny Bryan
venue_name: National Center for Ecological Analysis and Synthesis (NCEAS)
description:

Jenny's description for her talk:

"We'll learn a bit about specific packages (reprex, datapasta) and the role small examples can play in sharpening your R chops. We'll hopefully also try something completely new (to me!) as a way to explore productive habits and mindset for self-taught coders."

This will be a popular event so please only RSVP if you can attend.

As always we welcome people regardless of gender, but our group is intended for those who identify with a gender minority (trans women, cis women, trans men, non-binary, other). We expect all attendees to abide by our Code of Conduct.

name: Santa Barbara R-Ladies 2019 Kick-Off Meetup
description:
Join us for our first Santa Barbara R-Ladies meetup of 2019!

SB R-Ladies is growing quickly, and we're excited to see (and meet) you at our 2019 Kick-Off meetup on January 24th. We'll give a brief introduction to the group, get your ideas for events/topics you'd like to see in the new year, and mingle to continue building our growing coding community. Small snacks, refreshments, and hex stickers will be provided!

Please RSVP for this event so we can plan accordingly.

We'll look forward to seeing you on Decker's Deck (2nd floor, Bren Hall) on January 24th. *If it's raining, we have a backup room reserved at Bren (so the event will happen rain or shine).*

Anyone with an interest in R is encouraged to participate. It doesn't matter if you never used R or if you are an R expert. The goal is to promote R, exchange knowledge and foster a supportive community for those who identify with a gender minority (trans women, cis women, trans men, non-binary, other). We expect all attendees to abide by our Code of Conduct.

Parking: for those of you joining us from off-campus, you can park in Lot 10 (near the roundabout where Hwy 217 meets UCSB) after 5pm with a Visitor's Permit.

We will learn things from the `usethis` and `here` packages, and draw from Jenny Bryan and Jim Hester's "What they forgot to teach you about R" lessons (https://jennybc.github.io/wtf-2019-rsc/).

Tentative schedule:

- 5:30 drinks and networking
- 5:45 presentation & hands-on
- 6:45 drinks and networking

Looking forward to seeing you!

An and Sam will teach useful functions for data tidying, wrangling and visualization using tidyverse packages & functions (e.g. dplyr, tidyr, ggplot2, forcats, etc.). This session will be great for R users at any level, whether it's your first time exploring the tidyverse or if you're refreshing your wrangling skills!

There are opportunities for active coding in this session, so bring your computer with R and RStudio installed, and (if you don't have them already) install packages tidyverse, janitor, and here:

install.packages("tidyverse")

name: What R we doing in cancer research?*
description:
*This event is a collaboration of Lyon Data Science (https://www.meetup.com/Lyon-Data-Science/) with R-Ladies Lyon. Please register for this event at https://www.meetup.com/Lyon-Data-Science/events/259188960/

For this new session of Lyon Data Science, three cancer researchers from the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) will discuss diverse approaches in studying cancer with applications in R.

First, Dr. Virani will present a surveillance method focused on predictions of cancer incidence trends into the future to determine magnitude and burden over time. Next, Dr. Mariosa will discuss how to use genetic information to identify cancer risk factors using Mendelian randomization. Finally, Dr. Lennon will present examples of determining how different weight trajectories throughout lifetime relate to cancer risk.

name: Reflections from an R Lady in the Untidyverse of Cancer Research
description:
Welcome to our first event! It's free!

R-Ladies Lyon is pleased to welcome Dr. Hilary Robbins, scientist at the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC/WHO) in Lyon, France.

Her research develops and applies risk-based approaches to cancer screening, with a current focus on lung cancer screening.

Dr. Robbins will give a brief overview of her career thus far in cancer research, including how R fits into her profile as a researcher. She will discuss how she came to use R, an application from her current research (predicting risk of lung cancer during CT screening), some tips and tricks with her favorite tidyverse packages, and a few reflections about being an R lady in a male-dominated field.

Presenter: Dr. Hilary Robbins
Title: Reflections from an R Lady in the Untidyverse of Cancer Research
Twitter: @hilaryarobbins
https://www.linkedin.com/in/hilary-robbins-6a840223/
https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=ehL9SRcAAAAJ&hl=en

The talk will be held in English but you can ask your questions in French and we will help you translate. R-Ladies offers a platform for women to present their work and everyone is welcome to attend! Pizza and drinks will be provided after the presentation.

Follow us on twitter! @RLadiesLyon

name: *Pre-event*co-learning: dplyr, what happened so far up to episode 8?!
description:
On Monday, RLadies-Lyon are welcoming Romain Fran√ßois, creator of dplyr to Lyon where will be introducing new functions in the soon to be released dplyr 0.9.0 R package.

Us RLadies-Lyon are planning an informal pre-event on a rainy weekend in a warm coffee shop with a co-learning twist, with the aim to catch up on what we may have missed up to episode 8 :-)

This plans to be an informal event on a long rainy weekend which uses Monday's event to motivate us to work our way through the online Advanced R textbook,
Found here:
https://adv-r.hadley.nz/foundations-intro.html

In particular, Chapter 13 on S3 objects, and the vctrs package, because this paragraph is gobbledegook to me right now!!

<<13.1 Introduction
S3 is R‚Äôs first and simplest OO system. S3 is informal and ad hoc, but there is a certain elegance in its minimalism: you can‚Äôt take away any part of it and still have a useful OO system. For these reasons, you should use it, unless you have a compelling reason to do otherwise. S3 is the only OO system used in the base and stats packages, and it‚Äôs the most commonly used system in CRAN packages.>>

Ladies, come and join us for a relaxed Sunday afternoon of coding fun.

Anyone with experience is HIGHLY ENCOURAGED TO ATTEND <3

√Ä dimanche

name: dplyr: episode 9, the rise of the vctrs
description:
RLadies-Lyon would like to welcome Romain Fran√ßois, creator of dplyr to Lyon! He will be introducing new functions in the soon to be released dplyr 0.9 R package.

The event will start promptly at 7pm and will be followed with a round table of informal questions until 9pm.

!!! AN EVENT NOT TO BE MISSED !!!

Find out more about about open-source software and come and ask all of your questions !! https://purrple.cat/blog/2018/03/22/i-m-not-looking-for-a-job

The talk will be in english. Questions can be asked in french also.

Summary
The future dplyr 0.9.0 has been in development for a few months. It brings
exciting new developments largely thanks to the vision and implementation
of underlying packages rlang and vctrs. dplyr is more robust and stable
because of that.

One of the most important changes is that expressions in mutate() and
summarise() can now return tibbles that are either packed or unpacked.

We'll go through the new proposed functions pick() and across() and how they fit together with other functions from dplyr, i.e. mutate() and summarise(), and beyond, e.g. pack() and unpack() from the newest version of tidyr.

name: Creating reproducible analyses and reports with R Markdown
venue_address_1: EPFL Innovation Park, Building F, 3rd Floor
description:
‚Ä¢ Title of talk ‚Ä¢
Creating reproducible analyses and reports with R Markdown

‚Ä¢ Speaker ‚Ä¢
Claudia Kasper (https://twitter.com/claudia_kasper)

‚Ä¢ Requirements ‚Ä¢
+ A laptop with R and RStudio installed.
+ R-package RMarkdown (install.packages('rmarkdown‚Äô)) and ggplot2 (install.packages(‚Äòggplot2‚Äô) installed.
+ This is a beginner course. Having used basic commands in R before is sufficient, but no knowledge of markdown, latex or anything similar is required.

There will be internet access provided by the host.

‚Ä¢ Who is Claudia Kasper ‚Ä¢
I am an animal geneticist currently working as a researcher at Agroscope in Posieux, FR, where I work on breeding sustainable pigs. I started my career as an evolutionary biologist, first working on primates, then switching to humans and finally fish and house mice. In all of those systems I was interested in finding out more about cooperation, the social structure enabling it and the genetic basis of this fascinating biological phenomenon. My research is strongly centred on statistics for which I am using R. Having used Mathematica in the beginning, I was missing a neat way to organise my R scripts and to make reports of my findings. After a lot of frustration and literally days of copy-pasting R output into Word documents I discovered RMarkdown a few years ago and I have been using it ever since. Apart from having neater scripts, I ‚Äòknit‚Äô reports of my results as Word or PDF documents, but also presentations and I am trying to do a webpage with RMarkdown. In my free time I play improvisational theatre in Bern in a group which I co-founded.

name: Using R to assess Eye-tracking data when investigating Psychological Processes
venue_address_1: EPFL Innovation Park, Building F, 3rd Floor
description:
‚Ä¢ Title of the talk ‚Ä¢
Using R to assess Eye-tracking data when investigating Psychological Processes

‚Ä¢ Speaker ‚Ä¢
Suzannah Stuijfzand ( https://twitter.com/stuijfzandsooz )

‚Ä¢ Schedule ‚Ä¢
18h00 Arrival
18h15 Presentation
19h30 - 20h30 Ap√©ro + networking

‚Ä¢ Who is Suzannah Stuijfzand ‚Ä¢
I am a research psychologist currently working as a post doc within the Lausanne Perinatal Research group led by Prof. Antje Horsch. The group investigates perinatal mental health, specifically we investigate the impact of stress and trauma in the perinatal period (the time before, during and after birth) on mothers and their families.
My background is firmly routine in developmental psychology. My research masters in development and socialization in childhood and adolescence and my PhD was on Cognitive processes and their association to Anxiety in young children. My career so far has led me from the UK to the Netherlands for my masters, back to the UK for my PhD and finally my post-doc has brought me here to Lausanne.
My research has necessitated an interest in diverse methodologies in an attempt to overcome the limitations in standard measures (i.e. reaction times) when studying children. I have also has to become accustomed to longitudinal data in order to study development. It is through these elements of my research that have brought me into contact with R in an attempt to make the best use of my data to answer my research questions.

description:

The tidyverse is a coherent system of packages for data manipulation, exploration and visualization that share a common design philosophy.

- ggplot2
- dplyr
- tidyr
- readr
- purrr
- tibble
- stringr

We'll be learning a bit about each of these core packages while demonstrating their functionalities!

Mine‚Äôs work focuses on innovation in statistics and data science pedagogy, with an emphasis on computing, reproducible research, student-centered learning, and open-source education as well as pedagogical approaches for enhancing retention of women and under-represented minorities in STEM. name: Gold star reproducibility by Saras Windecker
description:
We are very happy to welcome Saras, comming from Melbourne, for the next meeting. She will talk to us about reproducibility.
Please remember to fill in your real first and last name so that we can make prior authorization requests to enter the CNRS 2 days before the meetup.

See you soon :)

Abstract: Research using R underpins a wide array of applied decision-making. Growing recognition of irreproducibility of results produced using R raises concerns about the credibility of research and the reliability of decisions they inform. Although there are many aspects to reproducible research, one major problem is the basic lack of computational reproducibility of published work ‚Äì or the ability to rerun an analysis and reproduce the same results. There are many strategies for improving computational reproducibility, such as clear code structure, functional programming, and version control. Besides these tactics, however, we often find that analyses that reproduce on one machine or in one environment do not run in another, or do not run in the future. This problem is related to changing computing environments and software versions, and can be addressed using containerisation. In this talk, I will introduce containerisation and its implementation using an open-access R package. This introduction should be accessible to those who have never heard of or used containerisation before, as well as those who already actively use services such as Docker for containerisation.

After a brief mention of R's scoping rules & the beauty of R packages, we will revisit if-else structures, loops and some members of the apply family.

Throughout all of this we will mention Do`s and Don'ts based on acquired experience. Don't forget to bring your laptop to try out some related exercise on the spot.

Our guest speaker this time is Verena Pflieger, a Data Scientist at the statistical consultancy INWT Statistics (www.inwt-statistics.de). She is concerned mostly with the conceptualization of trainings and is active in teaching R and giving tutorials.

name: R-Ladies London visits R-Ladies Berlin
description:
We are happy to welcome R-Lady Grace from London at our additional meet-up session next week!

# Speaker details

Grace Meyer is a commercial analytics expert with proven success in advising business strategy based on data driven insights. She is currently based in London and works for the economics consultancy Oxera where she applies machine learning to strategic projects and is developing the data science and programming team. She is a mentor in the R-Ladies London chapter, uses R on a daily basis to crunch data and problem solve and presented at both UseR! and EARL last year.

# Dive into dplyr

Data is seldom already in a tidy format for you to start analysis on straight away. My personal experience confirms that about 80% of the analytics work-flow is massaging and crunching data into a useful state. R is a master of analytics and modelling which would be useless without its strong data manipulation functionality, especially from the tidyverse package dplyr. In this session we will learn the main verbs of dplyr and link them together with the magrittr pipe to create new data sets and get insight from our data. Then we will take a look at the verb extensions and other package functionality.

# What to bring

The session will be hands on so bring your own laptop with dplyr installed (examples will be based on in-build data sets). If you don't have the set-up, come along anyway to learn about this famous package.

# Important to know

This meetup will be aimed at all R abilities.

Please take note of the different time and place of this meet-up! We are going to meet in a small seminar room at the WeWork space at Kuhdamm. Therefore we need to know your complete name (question at RVSPs). Since the room is small we have a limit of participants this time. Therefore we kindly ask to register in the case you're able to join or to resign in time if required to provide your seat for another Lady!

After the session we would like to go for a drink and further chats to a close by bar or pizza place.

name: Hands-on training - R packages
description:

Her work focuses on predictive analytics, data quality, automated reporting and best practices in coding. She‚Äôs also the coordinator of INWT's data science trainings. Mira holds masters‚Äô degrees in statistics and psychology.

Our topic:
In her daily work, Mira develops R packages literally every day.
Mira‚Äôs talk on R packages covers everything you need to start writing your own R package: How to create a package and fill it with functions, document them properly and make sure that your package works correctly‚Ä¶ and, of course, how you can share your package with others.

The talk mainly addresses people who have already written their own R functions, but have few or no experience with writing R packages. You are of course welcome independent of your level of experience. You‚Äôll also have the opportunity to put all this into practice on your own computer, while Mira can help you if you run into problems.

Your preparation:
Just bring your own notebook and make sure that the R packages ‚Äúdevtools "roxygen2", "testthat", and "knitr‚Äù are installed.
In addition, if you use Windows, you need to install Rtools (not an R package; accessible here: https://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools).

Come and bring your laptop - our organiser Christin is back for a short visit in Berlin and would like to guide you through a tutorial showing you how to setup your first blog using Hugo and Netifly.
Please install or update the following packages: markdown & blogdown.
Instructions for the installation of Hugo is going to be posted in the comments soon. Stay tuned.

In the second part of the meetup we would like to code with you altogether, running for the first time a section we call "RetrinkR". Here, we would like to share a piece of code on GitHub and invite you to work with us on it. After a short introduction we are going to spend not more than an hour to have fun coding, learning and playing with R altogether.

If you have any chunk of code that you think that would be perfectly suitable - you are stuck and need a fresh view - get in touch with us here on meetup.

Also in case of any other questions regarding R in general, you would like give a presentation or a R package that you would like to be introduced by us - please drop us a line at [masked].

We are looking forward to see you soon!
Best
R-Ladies Berlin organisation team

name: satRday Berlin
description:
satRday Berlin is an R-focused conference that will be held on Saturday June 15th, 2019. Our goal is to help and grow the local R user community. We want to make this event as accessible as possible - by not requiring time off work, by not costing more than a day's wages, and by being supportive to new and under-represented community members.

More info: https://berlin2019.satrdays.org/

* Please note that you have to register via the event website to attend

name: Unleashing the power of biodiversity data - a visit from R-Ladies San Francisco
description:
Hello!

and welcome to another hands-on session at Babbel.

We are very happy that evolutionary biologist and R-Lady **Ciera Martinez** will join us all the way from R-Ladies San Francisco!

PART I
*****************************
With Ciera (@CieraReports) we will explore biodiversity data which can take many forms, from photographs of bird feathers from museums to 3D CT-scans of extinct animals. Natural History Museums and Botanical Gardens have been digitizing their collections for over ten years yielding billions of data points culminating in one of the most exciting data resources the world has to offer.

She will also speak about her work as a current Mozilla Science Fellow, where she and her team have been working at the Berkeley Institute of Data Science exploring what the world of biodiversity data has to offer. You learn more about this project at curiositydata.org. In addition to talking about her biodiversity data project, she will speak about data science in academia and will host a brief workshop on how to use R to map fossils of extinct animals. (text inspired by R-Ladies Paris, thanks <3)

PART II
*****************************
In the second part of the meetup we invite you to code together with us, running for the first time a section we call "RetrinkR". Here, we will share a piece of code on GitHub (or RStudio cloud) and invite you to work with us on it. After a short introduction we are going to spend not more than an hour to have fun coding, learning and playing with R altogether (ALL levels of experience with R welcome).

If you have any chunk of code that you think that would be perfectly suitable - you are stuck and need a fresh view - get in touch with us here on meetup or on twitter.

Also in case of any other questions regarding R in general, you would like give a presentation or a R package that you would like to be introduced by us - please drop us a line at [masked].

We are looking forward to see you soon!
Best
R-Ladies Berlin organisation team

*********************************************************************************
Please install or update the following packages:

install.packages("pacman")
pacman::p_load(ggplot2, ggmap, tidyverse, skimr, taxize, neotoma, maps)

Stay tuned.
*********************************************************************************

name: Hands-on TidyTuesday
description:
Hello!

and welcome to a hands-on TidyTuesday session at WeWork.

this time, we are going get creative in a smaller group with the newly released TidyTuesday data! (more info below: 1)

PART I
*****************************
We will kick off with the TidyTuesday Screencast by David Robinson. He usually uses a lot of tricks that can be awesome for other day-to-day R struggles. If we want to we can take time in between to discuss some insights in more detail. Coding along is possible :)
(more info below: 2)

PART II
*****************************
Then we will get creative ourselves. It's our turn to play, expore and try out different ways to visualize the dataset and tell its story. It is possible to work in small groups, by yourself or just to watch others and chip in from time to time. All R-knowledge-levels are welcome.

PART III
*****************************
Let's share and see what we came up with, what we struggled with and which solutions we found!

We are looking forward to seeing you!

Best
R-Ladies Berlin

*********************************************************************************
Please install or update the following packages:

install.packages("pacman")
pacman::p_load(ggplot2, tidyverse, skimr)

Stay tuned.
*********************************************************************************

More Info:
1: github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday
2: https://www.youtube.com/user/safe4democracy/videos

name: Hands on: Docker containers. Rational and a tutorial walk through.
description:
Hello!

and welcome to another hands-on session at Babbel. We are very happy that Amit Kothiyal and Evgeny Savin, two Data Scientists at Smava, will join us! They use Docker to deploy Machine Learning models in Smava's production environment.

DockeR
*****************************
Amit and Evgeny will explain the importance of using containerization particularly when using machine learning models on production and walk us through the creation of a Docker container.

Our speakers
*****************************
Amit holds a PhD from Erasmus University Rotterdam and has worked as a Research Scientist in Max Plank Institute Berlin before joining Smava.

Evgeny has an MsC degree from HU University Berlin and has worked as a data scientist in a number of commercial organisations in Berlin.

Further Info
*****************************
- any other questions regarding R in general
- you would like give a presentation
- you know of an R package that you would like to be introduced by us

--> please drop us a line at [masked]

We are looking forward to see you soon!
Best
R-Ladies Berlin organisation team

*********************************************************************************
Set-up your machine to join the hands-on part:
- (4 minutes) install and set-up docker: https://docs.docker.com/get-started/
- (10 minutes) pull r-base https://hub.docker.com/_/r-base $ docker pull r-base
- docker cheat sheet: https//www.docker.com/sites/default/files/Docker_CheatSheet_[masked]_0.pdf

* workshop
** pull an existing image and use it
*** pull
docker-hub: https://hub.docker.com/
docker pull r-base:3.1.3
docker images r-base # images that were pulled
*** launch
# interactive
$ docker run -ti --rm r-base
$ docker run -ti --rm r-base:3.1.3
# bash session
$ docker run -ti --rm r-base /bin/bash
# linking pwd
$ docker run -it --rm -v "$PWD":/data r-base /bin/bash
** develop your own image
$ docker build -t my_first_image .
$ docker run -ti --rm my_first_image
$ docker image rm my_fist_image
** publish it in registery

*********************************************************************************

name: rstudio::conf(2020) Watch Party
description:
Rstudio::conf(2020) watch party in cooperation with RStudio, RLadiesBerlin, BerlinR, and the Berlin RUG!

Let us enjoy the conference without having to trek to San Francisco. We'll watch and discuss live streams together, enjoy RStudio trinkets and have food and drinks as well.

Schedule
***********************************
5 pm - Just before the first keynote, a live-streamed pre-game event will feature short interviews with folks from RStudio as well as the wider R-Community. During this event, we will have an opportunity to interact with the host and guests in real time.

6pm - The pre-game event will lead directly into the keynote and session live-streams. We aim to watch the first two keynote talks of the conference together and we can pose questions to the speakers.

Keynotes:
- Open Source Software for Data Science, J.J. Allaire - Hosts, Founder and CEO RStudio
- Data, visualization, and designing with AI, Fernanda Viegas and Martin Wattenberg, Google

9pm - We draw the winners from a little raffle game we prepared :)

About rstudio::conf:
***********************************
Featuring two days of content with more than 70 sessions and lightning talks, rstudio::conf will welcome more than 2000 attendees to listen, discuss, and explore what‚Äôs possible with R and RStudio.

Link to Agenda: https://tinyurl.com/yyvyx66c

********************************************************************************
stay tuned for more details!

name: Getting started with R
description:
Hey there!

its the beginning of a new year and we are having a session for beginners... This time will be all about learning R :)

*You are already familiar with R*
come by and support the others or come and take the time to learn something you have been meaning to get a handle on for a long time!

*You are new to R and the community*
feel free to join, this is the meet-up for you!

The wonderful Lisa Hehnke (twitter: @dataplanes) will give an "Intro to R" and in our hands-on session you get to try it out yourself. Either join for some exercises or work on your own projects/ideas.

Meet Lisa
*********************************************
She is a researcher turned social data scientist who is working to address current societal challenges in order to make a difference and drive change. After obtaining her Master's degree in politics and public administration with specializations in management and quantitative research methods, Lisa worked as a researcher for computational social science and quantitative data analysis at the Universities of Konstanz, Hamburg, and Bielefeld. She currently develops a decentralized knowledge commons infrastructure with Liberate Science and serves as a steering committee member of the Open Science MOOC to make open the default setting for all global research.

Schedule:
*********************************************
18.30 - Arrival and Welcome
19.00 - Intro to R with Lisa
20.00 - Hands-on session: You can do it
20.30 - Keep going or Mingle

preparation
*********************************************
for the meet-up, try to have R and RStudio installed on your device, so that you are ready to go. If you run into problems, we can sort them out at the venue ;)
If possible, also pre-install these two packages by typing the following code into the console:
install.packages("tidyverse")
install.packages("rtweet")

you already want to get started?
*********************************************
here are some materials with which you can start

install.packages("swirl")
library(swirl)

contact
*********************************************
twitter: @RLadiesBerlin
please get in touch if you have any questions!

********************************************************************************
stay tuned for more details and preparation instructions :)

name: Coffee & Get-to-know-you
description:
Dear all,

Thanks for joining our group!

Join us for a cup of coffee and some networking on Saturday, 20th October in one of Vienna Coffeehouses.

We are planning a bigger kick off meeting at the end of November and we would love to hear your ideas and suggestions for our first event.

name: Hadley Wickham @ Joint Vienna<-R x R-Ladies Vienna March Event
description:
We are excited to announce that Hadley Wickham will be the guest of the joint event organized by Vienna<-R and R-Ladies Vienna on March 18.

[About our speaker]

Hadley is chief scientist at R-Studio and well known for his contributions to the R programming language including his *tidyverse* packages like ggplot2, dplyr, readr and the software development package devtools.

[Agenda]

- Introduction to Vienna<-R

- Laura Vana (R-Ladies Vienna)
This joint event is the first meetup of R-Ladies Vienna this year so we will kick off the meeting with an introduction to the Vienna Chapter of R-Ladies and an overview of our ongoing and future initiatives and events.

- Hadley Wickham (RStudio)

[Q & A]

If you want to ask Hadley or myself any questions during the Q&A session please let us know, for example with a message below or an email to [masked].

[Networking]

After the talks we are planning a networking session with some food and
drinks.

Looking forward to seeing you there!

name: Workshop - Introduction to R
venue_name: Vienna University of Economics and Business
description:
Dear all,

The goal of our next meetup is for our attendees to become acquainted with R and R Studio in order to start their data analytics journey.

We'll cover:

* Brief intro to R as a programming language
* Functions, data structures, data types
* Reading data into R
* Basic data visualization in R
* R packages
* Examples and use cases

If time allows we will briefly introduce to you Rmarkdown and give a glimpse into how to make your analysis more reproducible.

We recommend you bring your own laptop where you have
R and RStudio installed (https://cran.r-project.org/ and https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/).
In case you want to install Rmarkdown you can follow the instructions at https://bookdown.org/yihui/rmarkdown/installation.html

See you soon!

name: Session 1: Bayesian statistics study group
venue_name: Vienna University of Economics and Business
description:

Looking forward to seeing you there!

name: Joint Event: Women in Tech Initiatives Meetup @PyDays
description:
Technologists create products and services and in doing so affect our everyday lives now and in the future. If these products and services are supposed to serve our society as a whole, we need a lot of diverse and creative perspectives reflecting the richness of our communities. Therefore, we strongly believe that striving to increase diversity among technologists should be a major goal.

On our pursuit for diversity, one of the most encouraging things we can do is to highlight those women who already work on great things within their respective industries, provide them platforms to share their knowledge and inspire by their example.

In Vienna, a range of initiatives promoting gender diversity in STEM (science, technology, engineering & math) exist. To increase visibility as well as to facilitate exchange of ideas and getting-to-know-each-other amongst these initiatives, a session solely dedicated to these groups and projects will take place during PyDays Vienna (https://www.pydays.at)

Enlisted Initiatives:
- Co-Mentoring Programme - Women in Data Science
- Feminist Python Meetup for Women* and Non-Binary Folks in Vienna
- Feminist Linux Meetup f√ºr Frauen*, Non-Binary*, Trans* und Inter* Personen
- diebin.at - Verein zur F√∂rderung emanzipatorischer Informations- und Kommunikationstechnologien
- R-Ladies Vienna
- IEEE Women in Engineering

People of all genders are welcome to attend our event.
Find out more at: https://www.pydays.at/womenintech/

name: Extending R with Packages with Bettina Gr√ºn
venue_name: Vienna University of Economics and Business
description:
Dear all,

It is our pleasure to announce Bettina Gr√ºn as our next speaker for this Friday's Meetup.

Bettina will be giving a talk on

"Extending R with Packages".

Bettina is an Associate Professor of Applied Statistics at JKU Linz. She is an active member of the R community and has written our co-authored numerous R packages such as flexmix, topicmodels, bayesmix, arules, exams, movMF and betareg. Moreover, she is an ordinary member of the R Foundation and currently serves as Editor-in-Chief for the Journal of Statistical Software.

After the talk we will go for some drinks in one of the restaurants at the WU Campus.

We are looking forward to seeing you on Friday!

name: Summer opening get together
description:
Dear all,

As our last event before the summer we would be happy if you joined us for some drinks and networking next Tuesday on the Donau Kanal at Summer Stage. It would be a great opportunity to get to know each other or simply catch up.

Next events will resume after the summer!

We are looking forward to meeting you!

To those of you who can‚Äôt join, we wish you a happy summer!

name: Joint November Event RLadies x Vienna<-R
description:
Dear all,

We are happy to announce Achim Zeileis and Joel Gotsch for our next joint event with the ViennaR meetup group. This time the Meetup is hosted at Raiffeisen Bank International (at Stadtpark, 1030 Vienna - "Skyroom").

Topics:

1. Achim Zeileis: Distributional Regression Forests for Probabilistic Modeling and Forecasting.

2. Joel Gotsch: Dynamic FX Margin Optimization

After the talks you are invited to join the networking session with refreshments provided by our host RBI.

See you soon!

name: R-Ladies Kyiv - Launch Event
description:
R-Ladies Kyiv is pleased to announce that we‚Äôll be hosting our official launch event!

Come enjoy an evening of R-related discussion, and a chance to network with other R-users from across the city on Tuesday, July 2nd, 2019 at Parus Business Center, 1991 Civic Center.

Feel free to share the event invite with all those who may be interested!

Event is free to attend, registration is required prior to the event:
https://forms.gle/TFmwsK2h5oV2cdMh8

1991 Civic Tech Center is located in the heart of Ukrainian capital to inspire civic tech startups and community with location, space, connections, acceleration programs, events and each other.

Follow us on Facebook:
https://www.facebook.com/RLadiesKyiv/

Agenda:
19:00 - Welcome from R-Ladies Global Team
19:30 - Introduction in R Markdown by Yevheniia Drozdova, data analyst and journalist at Texty.org.ua
20:00 - Obtaining meteorological data and using them to "enhance" environmental monitoring data.
21:00 - Networking

name: FB Live with Mehrdad (Data Scientist @ FB)
description:
If you're curious about introduction to Data Science, join us for an exclusive FB Live AMA session with Mehrdad Honarkhah, a Data Scientist at Facebook.

To join the event you should be a member of Developer Circle Kyiv group: https://www.facebook.com/groups/332298634106277/

Please post your questions here in the comments prior to the event.

=====

Mehrdad Honarkhah is a Data Scientist at Facebook‚Äôs Spatial Computing Research and Connectivity teams. His main focus is on statistical and predictive models to help improve connectivity around the world. Before joining Facebook, he worked on providing predictive risk models for catastrophic events and introduced innovative capital market transaction vehicles. After receiving two engineering degrees, he got his PhD from Stanford University on Spatial Statistics.

name: 2019 VR/AR Challenge
description:
R-Ladies Kyiv pleased to announce a partnership with Facebook Developer Circle Kyiv and invite our members to take part in community challenge!

There are over $165,000 USD in prizes for regional and global winners, with the global first place winner walking away with up to $25,000 USD in prizes.

Developer Circles will launch a free Data Science and Machine Learning program in a couple of months and prepare a lot of interesting workshops too!

Developer Circles is kicking off the third annual Developer Circles Community Challenge. Our goal is to bring together developers from across the globe to build software using React360, Spark AR, or HTML5 Games to give people the power to connect with friends and family, build communities, and grow businesses. Developers are invited to submit software across one of three categories: Productivity and Utility, Gaming and Entertainment, and Social Good.

Located in over 130 cities around the world with a community of over 200,000 developers, Developer Circles from Facebook is a great way for people to join a network of developers to collaborate, learn, and code together. For the 2019 Developer Circles Community Challenge, local Developer Circles will host in-person Build Days, where developers can meet each other, learn about Facebook Developer Products, and build solutions together. Visit the Challenge website to join a Build Day in your city and check back as new dates and cities will be added.

How to Enter:
Free to attend, great prizes and free training in specific technologies.
Join local Developer Circle to collaborate with other developers.

https://www.facebook.com/groups/332298634106277/

We can't wait to see what our global developer community builds! #DevCChallenge #DevCKyiv #BuildDayKyiv

name: Tech lunch: Data Science study group
description:
R-Ladies Kyiv is pleased to announce that we‚Äôll be hosting our first Tech Lunch event together with Facebook Developer Circle Kyiv!

Come enjoy an evening of R-related discussion, and a chance to network with other R-users from across the city on Saturday, September 7, 2019 in Kyiv.
Our main focus will be to create study group and learn Data Science together!

Stay updated and join our telegram channel:
https://t.me/DeveloperCircle

Lunch is sponsored by Facebook Circle Kyiv.
https://www.facebook.com/groups/332298634106277/

Registration is open : https://forms.gle/j16m5ACd1tENviyFA

We will notify selected participants prior to the event.

name: Cluster Analysis in R: Basic Concepts and Methods
description:
!!! Event is free to attend, registration is required prior to the event.
Before submitting you're going, make sure you have filled this form: https://forms.gle/tKM8gFPy5wmidfXy7

Wow, it's third meetup of R-Ladies Kyiv!

Wonderful Galina Dychko (https://www.linkedin.com/in/galina-dychko/) will share her knowledge of basic concepts and methods of cluster analysis in R.

The lecture is aimed to provide a beginner-friendly overview of the basic cluster analysis techniques. The focus is on the key mathematical concepts of the main clustering algorithms and how multidimensional visualization helps us to identify groups of similar objects.
We will briefly cover how to use PCA, CCA and multidimensional scaling for data visualization, how to choose clustering distance measure and run k-means, hierarchical and spectral clustering algorithms with R. Half of lecture will focus on the theoretical concepts and a half on the practical examples.

Good to have:
- basic understanding of data analysis concepts
- basic understanding of PCA and CCA algorithms
- no previous strong knowledge of R programming

name: Data streaming with Apache Flink
description:
Ververica is the new name of data Artisans, the company founded in 2014 by the original creators of Apache Flink¬Æ. with headquartered in Berlin, Germany.

They started Data Artisans (now Ververica) because they saw the need for a large-scale data processing technology that is open source and at the same time properly rooted in long-tested principles and architectures from the database and distributed systems fields.

From the very beginning, they developed Apache Flink¬Æ in the open source, and they witnessed and led Flink‚Äôs rapid community growth and industry adoption.

The meetup will be about Stateful Stream Processing
The volume of data generated in the world continues to grow steadily. The ability to process these in real time not only opens up new applications but often becomes a necessity to maintain a competitive edge. We will discuss how the horizontally scalable Stateful Stream Processing responds to these new demands and why it can be considered an evolution of the Batch Processing approach. We will also look at the technical complexities involved in building such distributed systems and how they have been resolved in Apache Flink.

Speaker: Alexander Fedulov, Solutions Architect at Ververica

Alexander Fedulov is a Solutions Architect at Ververica (formerly data Artisans). He is advising customers with application design, system integration and performance tuning. Prior to joining Ververica, Alexander worked as a developer and consultant in a variety of companies based in Berlin. He has a Masters Degree (M.Sc.) from the Technical University of Hamburg (TUHH).

Event is totally free to attend, but RSVP is required.
Food and drinks for networking part will be provided:

More information and registration is here:
https://apacheflink.splashthat.com

Follow announcements at FB event: www.facebook.com/events/[masked]
